Great!

Could you drop `hX₁` by inserting a `normalize` call in the right place in the conclusion, and perhaps derive this theorem from it?
What do you mean by a "normalize call"?

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion (R : Type*) [CommRing R] [IsDomain R] [IsPrincipalIdealRing R]--cannot comment this! ```
Are you sure you want to change this file?
Surely not... 😄

```suggestion
/-- The bijection `normalizedFactorsEquivSpanNormalizedFactors.symm` between the set of prime
```
What do you mean by: `--cannot comment this!`
Well, I know what you mean but I don't know why you felt necessary to add this comment
I don't know what you mean. Are you thinking Lean should find the `DecidableEq` on `Associates` automatically from the existing context?
Because all these variables are in scope, so I would expect that it is not necessary to call them again. In the previous theorem none of them was needed. Is it because of the `open Classical`?

> I don't know what you mean. Are you thinking Lean should find the `DecidableEq` on `Associates` automatically from the existing context?

No, I would expect that it automatically finds `(R : Type*) [CommRing R] [IsDomain R] [IsPrincipalIdealRing R]` and that I only need to manually add the `DecidableEq` on `Associates`.
Why not add the requisite decidability instance to `Ideal.count_normalizedFactors_eq` and then to here?

```suggestion
  all_goals
```

```suggestion
        [DecidableEq <| Associates (Ideal R)] [∀ (p : Associates <| Ideal R) , Decidable (Irreducible p)]
```
and then 
```lean
theorem Ideal.count_normalizedFactors_eq {p x : Ideal R} [hp : p.IsPrime] {n : ℕ} (hle : x ≤ p ^ n)
    [DecidableEq (Ideal R)] (hlt : ¬x ≤ p ^ (n + 1)) : (normalizedFactors x).count p = n :=
```
removing the section and classical scope.
Very nice, thanks!
This should be erased (similarly below).
`normalizedFactorsEquivSpanNormalizedFactors.symm` does not appear in the statement of the theorem...
The proof should be indented two spaces to start with, not four
It is indented with two spaces, no?

You could make this
```suggestion
theorem count_normalizedFactorsSpan_eq_count' {r X : R} (hr : r ≠ 0) (hX : Prime X) :
    Multiset.count (normalize X) (normalizedFactors r) =
      Multiset.count (Ideal.span {X} : Ideal R) (normalizedFactors (Ideal.span {r})) := by
```
and then prove your original theorem with
```
  simpa [hX₁] using count_normalizedFactorsSpan_eq_count' hr hX
```
Done, thanks!
Why this change?
Because these variables have now been added globally and are no longer needed in the proof.

On second look, I don't think `normalizedFactorsSpan` makes sense as a name segment, so should be `normalizedFactors_span` in both cases.

Also, I think the name would make more sense if the conclusion was stated in the opposite direction.

OK, I will change them to `normalizedFactors_span`, but concerning the "opposite direction", are you suggesting that the first (rsp. the second) theorem becomes `count_eq_normalizedFactorsSpan` and similarly with `'` ?

In this direction I guess I'd go for `count_normalizedFactors_eq_count_normalizedFactors_span` which isn't so great - but I do think you want to include `span`. `count_normalizedFactors_span_eq_count` would work if you changed the conclusion. That might be a good idea anyway - the LHS right now seems simpler than the RHS.
I agree with Ruben. Flipping the equality and naming the lemmas `count_span_normalizedFactors_eq`, `count_span_normalizedFactors_eq_of_normUnit` and `count_associates_factors_eq`.
Thanks, done!

```suggestion
    [∀ (p : Associates <| Ideal R), Decidable (Irreducible p)]
```

**[lint-style]** reported by [reviewdog](https://github.com/reviewdog/reviewdog) :dog:
```suggestion Multiset.count (Ideal.span {X} : Ideal R) (normalizedFactors (Ideal.span {r})) = ```

```suggestion
  have hIrred : Irreducible (span {X}) := Prime.irreducible <| prime_span_singleton_iff.mpr hX
  have hneq0 : span {r} ≠ 0 := by simp only [Submodule.zero_eq_bot, ne_eq, span_singleton_eq_bot,
    hr, not_false_eq_true]
  have := multiplicity_eq_multiplicity_span (R := R) (a := X) (b := r)
  rw [multiplicity_eq_count_normalizedFactors (Prime.irreducible hX) hr,
    multiplicity_eq_count_normalizedFactors hIrred hneq0, normalize_apply,
    normUnit_eq_one, Units.val_one, one_eq_top, mul_top, Nat.cast_inj] at this
  simp only [normalize_apply, this]
```
I feel it's confusing when `rw` introduces extra goals. Adding some `have`s beforehand hopefully makes it clearer. Also `r ≠ 0 → span {r} ≠ 0` should perhaps be a lemma in mathlib?

```suggestion
theorem count_span_normalizedFactors_eq_of_normUnit {r X : R}
    (hr : r ≠ 0) (hX₁ : normUnit X = 1) (hX : Prime X) :
```
Very nitpicky, but this is perhaps easier to read at a glance.
